<details>
<summary> 5th COMPLAINT : CLUMSINESS (Incoordination)</summary>
<ol>
<li>SITE &amp; LATERALITY:
        <ol>
<li>Which limbs affected? (Upper/Lower/Both, Right/Left/Bilateral)</li>
<li>Is it more on one side?</li>
<li>Does it affect fine motor skills more or gross motor skills?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ONSET (O):
        <ol>
<li>When did you first notice the clumsiness?</li>
<li>Was it sudden or gradual?</li>
<li>Any specific event that triggered it? (e.g., illness, medication
            change, trauma)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>DURATION (D):
        <ol>
<li>How long have you had this problem? (Days/Weeks/Months/Years)</li>
<li>Is it constant or intermittent? If intermittent, how long do
            episodes last?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PROGRESSION (P):
        <ol>
<li>Is the clumsiness getting worse, better, or staying the same?</li>
<li>If worsening, how quickly?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>AGGRAVATING/RELIEVING FACTORS (A/R):
        <ol>
<li>Is it worse when you are tired or stressed?</li>
<li>Does anything make it better (e.g., concentrating hard, specific
            posture)?</li>
<li>Is it worse with eyes open or closed? (Less relevant for pure
            cerebellar, but good to ask)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ASSOCIATED SYMPTOMS:
        <ol>
<li><u>Weakness</u> in the affected limbs?</li>
<li><u>Numbness or tingling</u>?</li>
<li><b>Tremor</b>? (Resting, intention/action tremor - e.g., when
            reaching for an object)</li>
<li>Difficulty with specific tasks?
            <ol>
<li>Writing (handwriting changed?)</li>
<li>Buttoning clothes, tying shoelaces</li>
<li>Using cutlery, drinking from a cup (spilling?)</li>
<li>Knitting, sewing, playing musical instruments (as in video
                example)</li>
<li>Difficulty picking up small objects?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><em>Speech changes</em>? (Slurred, slow, difficult to understand -
            dysarthria)</li>
<li><em>Swallowing difficulties</em> (dysphagia)?</li>
<li><em>Vision changes</em>? (Blurred vision, double vision, nystagmus
            - "eyes jumping")</li>
<li><b>Balance problems / Unsteadiness</b>? (See next section)</li>
<li>Headache, vomiting, altered consciousness? (Signs of ↑ICT)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>IMPACT ON DAILY LIFE:
        <ol>
<li>How has this affected your daily activities (e.g., self-care,
            work, hobbies)?</li>
<li>Are you worried about it?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</details>
<br/>


<details>
<summary> 6th COMPLAINT : BALANCE PROBLEMS &amp; GAIT DIFFICULTIES
      (Postural Instability)</summary>
<ol>
<li>SITE (S) &amp; NATURE OF THE PROBLEM:
        <ol>
<li>How would you describe your balance problem or walking difficulty?
            <ol>
<li>Do you feel unsteady on your feet?</li>
<li>Is it a problem with starting to walk (initiating gait),
                turning, or stopping?</li>
<li>Swaying while walking or standing?</li>
<li>Feeling like you are "about to fall"?</li>
<li>Staggering or veering to one side?</li>
<li>Difficulty walking in a straight line?</li>
<li>Do you feel like you are walking "as if drunk"?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>Is it a feeling of dizziness or lightheadedness, or true
            unsteadiness and imbalance?
            <ol>
<li>Do you experience vertigo (a sensation of the room spinning
                around you)?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ONSET (O):
        <ol>
<li>When did you first start noticing problems with your balance or
            walking?</li>
<li>Was the onset gradual or did it come on suddenly?</li>
<li>Was it associated with any specific event, illness, medication
            change, or injury?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>DURATION (D) :
        <ol>
<li>How long has this been an issue? (Days/Weeks/Months/Years)</li>
<li>Is the problem constant, or does it come and go (intermittent)? If
            intermittent, how long do episodes last and how frequent are they?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>AGGRAVATING/RELIEVING FACTORS (A/R):
        <ol>
<li>What makes the balance or gait problems worse?
            <ol>
<li>Walking on uneven ground or in the dark?</li>
<li>Turning quickly or changing direction?</li>
<li>Being in narrow spaces or crowded areas?</li>
<li>When distracted or trying to do two things at once?</li>
<li>Fatigue or stress?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>What makes it better or helps you manage?
            <ol>
<li>Does holding onto something or using a walking aid (cane,
                walker) help?</li>
<li>Are there any cues that help you overcome freezing (e.g.,
                stepping over lines on the floor, rhythmic counting, music)?</li>
<li>Is it better or worse with your eyes open or closed? (Helps
                differentiate, e.g., Romberg's implication)</li>
<li>Do any medications help?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<br/>
<li>CHARACTER/TYPE (C):</li>
<ol>
<li><b>Character of Gait:</b>
<ol>
<li>Do you take small, shuffling steps (festinating gait)?</li>
<li>Do you have difficulty picking up your feet when walking?</li>
<li>Do you find yourself speeding up unintentionally and then having
              trouble stopping (festination)?</li>
<li>Do you experience "freezing" where your feet feel glued to the
              floor, especially in doorways, when trying to start walking, or
              when turning?</li>
<li>Have you noticed a reduced arm swing when walking?</li>
<li>Do you have a stooped posture when walking?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><b>Character of Balance:</b>
<ol>
<li>Do you sway when standing still?</li>
<li>Do you feel you might fall easily, especially when pushed
              slightly, when turning, or when reaching for something?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
<li>RADIATION (R): (Less about radiation of a sensation, more about
        spread/evolution of the difficulty)
        <ol>
<li>Has the type of balance or walking problem changed or have new
            difficulties emerged over time?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ASSOCIATED SYMPTOMS (A):
        <ol>
<li><b>History of falls</b>?
            <ol>
<li>If yes, how many times have you fallen?</li>
<li>What were the circumstances of the falls? (e.g., tripping,
                turning, freezing)</li>
<li>Did you sustain any injuries from the falls?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><u>Tremor</u> (shaking), especially at rest?</li>
<li><u>Stiffness and slowness</u> of movements?</li>
<li><u>Clumsiness</u> in your hands or legs?</li>
<li><em>Speech changes</em> (e.g., soft, monotone, slurred -
            dysarthria)?</li>
<li><em>Swallowing difficulties</em> (dysphagia)?</li>
<li><em>Vision changes</em> (e.g., blurred vision, double vision,
            "eyes jumping" - nystagmus)?</li>
<li>Weakness in your legs?</li>
<li>Numbness, tingling, or altered sensation in your feet or legs?
            (Suggests possible sensory ataxia component)</li>
<li>Dizziness or lightheadedness, especially on standing up (could be
            orthostatic hypotension)?</li>
<li>Headache, nausea, or vomiting?</li>
<li>Tinnitus (ringing in ears) or hearing loss? (Suggests possible
            vestibular component)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PROGRESSION (P):
        <ol>
<li>Have your balance and walking problems worsened, improved, or
            stayed the same over time?</li>
<li>If worsening, how quickly has this happened?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PATTERN (P):
        <ol>
<li>Are there specific situations, environments, or times of day when
            your balance or walking is noticeably better or worse?</li>
<li>Does it fluctuate with medication timing (if applicable)?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>RED FLAGS (R):
        <ol>
<li><b>Frequent falls occurring early in the disease course</b> (e.g.,
            within the first 1-3 years of symptom onset) can be a red flag for
            atypical parkinsonism or other conditions.</li>
<li>Rapidly progressive gait and balance deterioration.</li>
<li>Symmetrical onset of severe gait/balance issues without other
            typical PD signs.</li>
<li>Poor response of gait/balance issues to Parkinson's medications
            (if tried).</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>EFFECT ON LIFE (E) &amp; SEVERITY (S):
        <ol>
<li>How have these balance and walking difficulties affected your
            daily life and independence?
            <ol>
<li>Has it limited your mobility or ability to go out of the
                house?</li>
<li>Do you need assistance from another person for walking or
                transfers (e.g., getting out of a chair)?</li>
<li>Do you use any walking aids (cane, walker, wheelchair)?</li>
<li>Has it affected your ability to perform household chores,
                shop, or participate in hobbies?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>Do you have a fear of falling? How does this impact your
            activities?</li>
<li>On a scale of 0 to 10, with 0 being no problem and 10 being the
            worst imaginable difficulty:
            <ol>
<li>How would you rate the severity of your balance problems?</li>
<li>How would you rate the severity of your walking difficulty?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>


</details>



<details>
<summary> 7th COMPLAINT: TREMOR (Involuntary Shaking)</summary>
<ol>
<li>SITE (S):
        <ol>
<li>Where does the tremor occur? (e.g., Hands, fingers, arm, leg, jaw,
            chin, lips, tongue)</li>
<li>Is it on one side of the body (unilateral) or both (bilateral)?</li>
<li>If bilateral, did it start on one side and then spread to the
            other? Which side started first?</li>
<li>Is it more prominent in the upper or lower limbs?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ONSET (O):
        <ol>
<li>When did you (or someone else) first notice the tremor?
            (Years/Months ago)</li>
<li>Was the onset sudden or did it develop gradually over time?</li>
<li>Was there any specific event, illness, or medication started
            around the time it began?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>DURATION (D) :
        <ol>
<li>How long have you had the tremor?</li>
<li>Is the tremor present all the time, or does it come and go
            (intermittent)?</li>
<li>If intermittent, how long do episodes last? How frequent are they?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>AGGRAVATING/RELIEVING FACTORS (A/R):
        <ol>
<li>What makes the tremor worse?
            <ol>
<li>Stress, anxiety, fatigue?</li>
<li>When concentrating on a task with another limb?</li>
<li>When walking?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>What makes the tremor better or temporarily disappear?
            <ol>
<li>Voluntary movement or action of the affected limb?</li>
<li>Sleep? (Tremor usually absent during sleep)</li>
<li>Alcohol? (Less typical for PD tremor, more for essential
                tremor)</li>
<li>Any medications?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>CHARACTER/TYPE (C) :
        <ol>
<li>Is it more noticeable when your limb is at rest (<u>Resting Tremor</u>)?
            (e.g., when your hand is resting in your lap)</li>
<li>Does it improve or disappear when you are using the limb for an
            action (e.g., reaching for an object, writing)?</li>
<li>Does it worsen when you are holding a posture (Postural Tremor)?
            (e.g., holding arms outstretched)</li>
<li>Can you describe the movement? (e.g., "pill-rolling" movement of
            fingers, back-and-forth)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<br/>
<li>RADIATION (R): (Less applicable for tremor itself, more about spread)
        <ol>
<li>Has the tremor spread from its original site to other parts of the
            body over time? If so, where?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ASSOCIATED SYMPTOMS (A):
        <ol>
<li><u>Stiffness</u> or rigidity in the limbs? (See next complaint)</li>
<li><u>Slowness of movement</u>? (Bradykinesia - see next complaint)</li>
<li>Difficulty with balance or walking?</li>
<li>Changes in handwriting (micrographia - becoming smaller and more
            cramped)?</li>
<li>Changes in speech (softer, monotone, hesitant - hypophonia)?</li>
<li>Difficulty with fine motor tasks (e.g., buttoning, cutting food)?</li>
<li>Masked facies (reduced facial expression)?</li>
<li>Pain or discomfort associated with the tremor or stiffness?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PROGRESSION (P):
        <ol>
<li>How has the tremor changed since it first started? (Become more
            noticeable, spread, amplitude increased?)</li>
<li>Has it changed in frequency or character?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PATTERN (P):
        <ol>
<li>Is it continuous when at rest, or does it have periods of being
            better and worse throughout the day?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>RED FLAGS (R): (For PD, red flags might indicate atypical parkinsonism
        or other conditions)
        <ol>
<li>Rapid progression of symptoms?</li>
<li>Early onset of severe balance problems or falls?</li>
<li>Early severe autonomic dysfunction (e.g., severe postural
            hypotension, urinary incontinence)?</li>
<li>Symmetrical onset of tremor?</li>
<li>Lack of response to Parkinson's medications (if tried)?</li>
<li>Presence of other neurological signs (e.g., cerebellar signs,
            pyramidal signs, eye movement abnormalities not typical for PD)?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>EFFECT ON LIFE (E):
        <ol>
<li>How does the tremor affect your daily activities (e.g., eating,
            dressing, writing, work, hobbies)?</li>
<li>Does it cause you embarrassment or social withdrawal?</li>
<li>How much does it bother you?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>SCALE (S):
        <ol>
<li>On a scale of 0 to 10, with 0 being no tremor and 10 being the
            worst imaginable tremor, how would you rate its severity at its
            worst? And on average?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>


</details>
<br/>
<details>
<summary> 8th COMPLAINT: STIFFNESS (Rigidity) &amp; SLOWNESS OF MOVEMENT
      (Bradykinesia/Akinesia)</summary>
<ol>
<li>SITE (S) &amp; LATERALITY:
        <ol>
<li>Where do you feel the stiffness or slowness? (e.g., Arms, legs,
            neck, trunk)</li>
<li>Is it on one side of the body or both? Did it start on one side?</li>
<li>Is it a general feeling of slowness, or difficulty initiating
            movements?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ONSET (O):
        <ol>
<li>When did you first notice the stiffness or slowness?</li>
<li>Was it sudden or gradual?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>DURATION (D) &amp; CHARACTER/TYPE (C):
        <ol>
<li>How long have these symptoms been present?</li>
<li>Are they constant or do they fluctuate?</li>
<li><b>Character of Stiffness:</b>
<ol>
<li>Is it a feeling of muscle tightness or resistance to movement?</li>
<li>Is it like a "cogwheel" (jerky resistance) or "lead-pipe"
                (smooth, constant resistance) if felt by an examiner or noticed
                by patient?</li>
<li>Is there associated pain or aching with the stiffness?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><b>Character of Slowness (Bradykinesia):</b>
<ol>
<li>Do you find it takes longer to do everyday tasks?</li>
<li>Difficulty starting movements (akinesia)?</li>
<li>Do movements become smaller or slower with repetition (e.g.,
                finger tapping, handwriting)?</li>
<li>Feeling of "freezing" where you get stuck, especially when
                starting to walk or turning?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>AGGRAVATING/RELIEVING FACTORS (A/R):
        <ol>
<li>What makes the stiffness or slowness worse? (e.g., Cold weather,
            inactivity, stress)</li>
<li>What makes it better? (e.g., Warmth, gentle exercise, medication -
            if on any)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>RADIATION (R): (Spread of symptoms)
        <ol>
<li>Has the stiffness or slowness spread to other parts of the body
            since onset?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>ASSOCIATED SYMPTOMS (A):
        <ol>
<li><u>Tremor</u> at rest?</li>
<li><b>Balance problems</b>, shuffling gait, difficulty turning?
            (Postural instability)</li>
<li>Difficulty getting out of a chair or turning in bed?</li>
<li>Reduced arm swing when walking?</li>
<li>Changes in handwriting (micrographia)?</li>
<li>Reduced facial expression (masked facies)?</li>
<li>Soft or monotone speech (hypophonia)?</li>
<li>Drooling of saliva?</li>
<li>Fatigue?</li>
<li><em>Non-Motor Symptoms:</em>
<ol>
<li>Loss of sense of smell (anosmia)?</li>
<li>Sleep disturbances (e.g., REM sleep behavior disorder - acting
                out dreams)?</li>
<li>Constipation?</li>
<li>Mood changes (depression, anxiety)?</li>
<li>Cognitive changes (difficulty with attention, planning,
                memory)?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PROGRESSION (P):
        <ol>
<li>How have these symptoms changed over time?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>PATTERN (P):
        <ol>
<li>Are there times of day when the stiffness/slowness is better or
            worse (e.g., "wearing off" of medication)?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>RED FLAGS (R): (As above, for atypical features)
        <ol>
<li>Early severe dementia?</li>
<li>Prominent cerebellar signs (ataxia beyond what's expected from
            PD)?</li>
<li>Significant gaze palsies?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>EFFECT ON LIFE (E):
        <ol>
<li>How do these symptoms limit your daily activities (dressing,
            bathing, walking, household chores)?</li>
<li>Has it impacted your independence? Your mood?</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>SCALE (S):
        <ol>
<li>On a scale of 0-10, how would you rate the severity of your
            stiffness? Your slowness?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>


</details>

